msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1002
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1003
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"/resources/views/components/accordion.blade.php\n"
"/resources/views/components/accordion/item.blade.php\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1008
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1009
msgid "This directory structure allows you to render the accordion component and its item like so:"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1009
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1010
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<x-accordion>\n"
"    <x-accordion.item>\n"
"        ...\n"
"    </x-accordion.item>\n"
"</x-accordion>\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1018
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1019
msgid "However, in order to render the accordion component via `x-accordion`, we were forced to place the \"index\" accordion component template in the `resources/views/components` directory instead of nesting it within the `accordion` directory with the other accordion related templates."
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1020
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1021
msgid "Thankfully, Blade allows you to place an `index.blade.php` file within a component's template directory. When an `index.blade.php` template exists for the component, it will be rendered as the \"root\" node of the component. So, we can continue to use the same Blade syntax given in the example above; however, we will adjust our directory structure like so:"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1021
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1022
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"/resources/views/components/accordion/index.blade.php\n"
"/resources/views/components/accordion/item.blade.php\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1027
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1028
#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"data-properties-attributes\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Title ####
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1027
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1028
#, no-wrap
msgid "Data Properties / Attributes"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1030
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1031
msgid "Since anonymous components do not have any associated class, you may wonder how you may differentiate which data should be passed to the component as variables and which attributes should be placed in the component's [attribute bag](#component-attributes)."
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1032
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1033
msgid "You may specify which attributes should be considered data variables using the `@props` directive at the top of your component's Blade template. All other attributes on the component will be available via the component's attribute bag. If you wish to give a data variable a default value, you may specify the variable's name as the array key and the default value as the array value:"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1034
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1035
#, no-wrap
msgid "    <!-- /resources/views/components/alert.blade.php -->\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1036
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1037
#, no-wrap
msgid "    @props(['type' => 'info', 'message'])\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1042
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1043
msgid "Given the component definition above, we may render the component like so:"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1046
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1047
#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"accessing-parent-data\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Title ####
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1046
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1047
#, no-wrap
msgid "Accessing Parent Data"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1049
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1050
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sometimes you may want to access data from a parent component inside a child component. In these cases, you may use the `@aware` directive. For example, imagine we are building a complex menu component consisting of a parent `<x-menu>` and child `<x-menu.item>`:\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1054
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1055
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <x-menu color=\"purple\">\n"
"        <x-menu.item>...</x-menu.item>\n"
"        <x-menu.item>...</x-menu.item>\n"
"    </x-menu>\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1056
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1057
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `<x-menu>` component may have an implementation like the following:\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1058
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1059
#, no-wrap
msgid "    <!-- /resources/views/components/menu/index.blade.php -->\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1060
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1061
#, no-wrap
msgid "    @props(['color' => 'gray'])\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1064
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1065
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <ul {{ $attributes->merge(['class' => 'bg-'.$color.'-200']) }}>\n"
"        {{ $slot }}\n"
"    </ul>\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1066
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1067
#, no-wrap
msgid "Because the `color` prop was only passed into the parent (`<x-menu>`), it won't be available inside `<x-menu.item>`. However, if we use the `@aware` directive, we can make it available inside `<x-menu.item>` as well:\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1068
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1069
#, no-wrap
msgid "    <!-- /resources/views/components/menu/item.blade.php -->\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1070
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1071
#, no-wrap
msgid "    @aware(['color' => 'gray'])\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1074
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1075
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <li {{ $attributes->merge(['class' => 'text-'.$color.'-800']) }}>\n"
"        {{ $slot }}\n"
"    </li>\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1076
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1077
#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"dynamic-components\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Title ###
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1076
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1077
#, no-wrap
msgid "Dynamic Components"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1079
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1080
msgid "Sometimes you may need to render a component but not know which component should be rendered until runtime. In this situation, you may use Laravel's built-in `dynamic-component` component to render the component based on a runtime value or variable:"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1081
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1082
#, no-wrap
msgid "    <x-dynamic-component :component=\"$componentName\" class=\"mt-4\" />\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1083
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1084
#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"manually-registering-components\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Title ###
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1083
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1084
#, no-wrap
msgid "Manually Registering Components"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1086
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1087
#, no-wrap
msgid "> {note} The following documentation on manually registering components is primarily applicable to those who are writing Laravel packages that include view components. If you are not writing a package, this portion of the component documentation may not be relevant to you.\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1090
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1091
msgid "However, if you are building a package that utilizes Blade components or placing components in non-conventional directories, you will need to manually register your component class and its HTML tag alias so that Laravel knows where to find the component. You should typically register your components in the `boot` method of your package's service provider:"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1093
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1094
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    use Illuminate\\Support\\Facades\\Blade;\n"
"    use VendorPackage\\View\\Components\\AlertComponent;\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Plain text
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1103
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1104
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    /**\n"
"     * Bootstrap your package's services.\n"
"     *\n"
"     * @return void\n"
"     */\n"
"    public function boot()\n"
"    {\n"
"        Blade::component('package-alert', AlertComponent::class);\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""
#
#. type: Title ####
# File: docs/8.x/blade.md, line: 1108
# File: docs/master/blade.md, line: 1109
#, no-wrap
msgid "Autoloading Package Components"
msgstr ""
